00:31:38.590 --> 00:31:40.450
JOSHUA SAFRAN: So
we made that movie

00:31:40.450 --> 00:31:43.660
with the producer and director
of "Crime After Crime".

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:46.100
We got together to
make this three minute

00:31:46.100 --> 00:31:49.070
trailer with mostly
volunteer cast and crew

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:52.590
of about 100 over six
days, in the Bay Area.

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:53.590
AUDIENCE: Two questions.

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:56.410
One, why did the
trial take so long?

00:31:56.410 --> 00:32:00.730
And two, is the book both about
your journey and the trial,

00:32:00.730 --> 00:32:03.280
or more about your upbringing?

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:05.594
JOSHUA SAFRAN: So the first
question on the trial,

00:32:05.594 --> 00:32:07.010
as Brian said, we
thought it would

00:32:07.010 --> 00:32:08.350
be relatively straightforward.

00:32:08.350 --> 00:32:10.370
There was a new
law passed in 2002

00:32:10.370 --> 00:32:13.540
that allowed women who'd been
convicted before California

00:32:13.540 --> 00:32:16.082
recognized what was then called
the battered woman's defense.

00:32:16.082 --> 00:32:18.581
There were all these women that
we're serving life in prison

00:32:18.581 --> 00:32:20.446
and never got to
present that defense.

00:32:20.446 --> 00:32:22.320
So I was like, well, if
you can get a lawyer,

00:32:22.320 --> 00:32:24.220
the lawyer can present it.

00:32:24.220 --> 00:32:29.030
So it took us a couple years
to just establish the evidence

00:32:29.030 --> 00:32:32.100
that we needed to show that she
had been battered conclusively.

00:32:32.100 --> 00:32:34.710
And we knew at that time
that the LA DA was really

00:32:34.710 --> 00:32:38.710
aggressively opposing the
release of all these women,

00:32:38.710 --> 00:32:42.050
unlike basically every
other county in California.

00:32:42.050 --> 00:32:43.580
Steve was his name.

00:32:43.580 --> 00:32:47.410
The LA DA had a real
opposition to these releases.

00:32:47.410 --> 00:32:52.120
So we ended up getting 12
percipient witness statements

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:55.066
declarations from all kinds of
people, including neighbors,

00:32:55.066 --> 00:32:56.690
and friends of the
batterer, et cetera,

00:32:56.690 --> 00:32:58.620
so we felt like we had
a pretty solid case.

00:32:58.620 --> 00:33:00.110
That was about two years in.

00:33:00.110 --> 00:33:01.000
We went to LA.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.290
We actually met with Steve
Cooley-- the LA DA himself--

00:33:04.290 --> 00:33:07.110
and got a plea deal that she
would get out for time served,

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:08.950
because of all
this new evidence.

00:33:08.950 --> 00:33:11.200
And not only do we
have it on a handshake,

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:13.240
we had it in writing.

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:15.880
And we unfortunately
ran into what could only

00:33:15.880 --> 00:33:18.470
be described as office
politics, believe it or not.

00:33:18.470 --> 00:33:21.460
So the woman who was the head
of the Appellate division--

00:33:21.460 --> 00:33:25.100
who was nominally in charge
of these kinds of cases--

00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:28.680
had never been consulted,
because we accidentally

00:33:28.680 --> 00:33:31.250
went to the top
guy, the elected DA.

00:33:31.250 --> 00:33:33.300
And she apparently
threw what was

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:36.330
called a political firestorm
and was yelling, and screaming,

00:33:36.330 --> 00:33:39.340
and throwing things in the DA's
office, and they got back to us

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:41.680
and said, well, we're
not honoring that.

00:33:41.680 --> 00:33:43.970
We are hereby
withdrawing the offer

00:33:43.970 --> 00:33:46.640
that you've already accepted,
and we will oppose you.

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:48.800
And at that point, we said,
well, that's unlawful,

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:49.549
and we'll sue you.

00:33:49.549 --> 00:33:52.520
And they said, OK, do your best.

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:56.290
So it ended up dragging on and
on, because we had to sue them.

00:33:56.290 --> 00:34:01.249
And, of course, the judicial
process is very slow,

00:34:01.249 --> 00:34:03.790
and then there were a number of
twists and turns in the case,

00:34:03.790 --> 00:34:08.106
including revelations that
not only was Debbie legally

00:34:08.106 --> 00:34:10.230
innocent and she had this
battered woman's defense,

00:34:10.230 --> 00:34:13.690
but she was actually factually
innocent, didn't do the killing

00:34:13.690 --> 00:34:15.719
herself, didn't
engineer the killing.

00:34:15.719 --> 00:34:17.980
In fact, the DA's
only witness that

00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:20.810
established that was a
paid police informant who

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:22.060
perjured himself on the stand.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:23.310
The DA's office knew about it.

00:34:23.310 --> 00:34:25.570
So it snowballed into this
bigger and bigger case,

00:34:25.570 --> 00:34:29.190
until finally a judge held
that they were circling

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:32.750
the wagons to protect their
professional reputations.

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:34.380
So the case really
for them became

00:34:34.380 --> 00:34:37.530
about covering up misdeeds,
because their own people

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:40.170
were going to be
fired, or worse,

00:34:40.170 --> 00:34:42.850
if the truth came
out in this case.

00:34:42.850 --> 00:34:44.949
So that was why the case
ended up taking so long.

00:34:44.949 --> 00:34:52.040
And it was a lead case in
this battered women's law

00:34:52.040 --> 00:34:54.719
in California and looked
to in various other states

00:34:54.719 --> 00:34:57.470
as to the entire
criminal justice system,

00:34:57.470 --> 00:34:59.950
how can this happen, how is
this going to work, et cetera.

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:02.280
So that was that answer.

00:35:02.280 --> 00:35:06.830
The book is really more just
my childhood story, basically

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:08.300
from 0 to 12.

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:10.335
And then I have a
chapter where I tie it

00:35:10.335 --> 00:35:11.654
into that work on that case.

00:35:11.654 --> 00:35:14.070
And I think it wasn't really
until I wrote the book that I

00:35:14.070 --> 00:35:18.800
really realized much
of my motivation

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:20.560
really, at least
in taking the case,

00:35:20.560 --> 00:35:23.460
but also in sticking
with it is that,

00:35:23.460 --> 00:35:26.290
again, the strange
feeling of powerlessness.

00:35:26.290 --> 00:35:29.220
And somehow this case
in a very real way

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:32.110
allowed me to prove to myself
at least that, oh, yeah, I

00:35:32.110 --> 00:35:32.830
can do something.

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:33.746
I can do what's right.

00:35:33.746 --> 00:35:35.350
And as I thought
about it, I thought

00:35:35.350 --> 00:35:38.360
what I really wanted when
I graduated from law school

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:42.399
and as I was becoming a
man was a time machine.

00:35:42.399 --> 00:35:43.940
I just wanted for
whatever-- you have

00:35:43.940 --> 00:35:46.450
these experiences in your life,
you want to go back in time,

00:35:46.450 --> 00:35:50.337
and help yourself
or help someone.

00:35:50.337 --> 00:35:52.420
And since I didn't have
time traveling capability,

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:53.860
maybe Google will develop that.

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:55.790
But at the time, that
wasn't available to me.

00:35:55.790 --> 00:35:58.456
So I thought well, the next best
thing is I can become a lawyer,

00:35:58.456 --> 00:36:00.690
and find people who
are similarly situated,

00:36:00.690 --> 00:36:03.670
and help them, and that
will metaphorically

00:36:03.670 --> 00:36:05.460
fix what I went through.

00:36:05.460 --> 00:36:09.820
AUDIENCE: So what part does
religion play in your life?

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.170
JOSHUA SAFRAN: That's
a great question.

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:14.600
Religion played a very
important role for me.

00:36:14.600 --> 00:36:17.730
As you heard, I was brought
up with star gazers,

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:21.170
and constellation
worshipers, and pagans.

00:36:21.170 --> 00:36:24.170
But more than anything, I
was brought up with nothing.

00:36:24.170 --> 00:36:27.970
Even at the most remote
areas of the counterculture,

00:36:27.970 --> 00:36:30.670
beyond on the perimeter, people
still celebrated Christmas.

00:36:30.670 --> 00:36:34.860
I mean, you could be an Indian
guru somewhere up in Oregon,

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:37.270
but you would still have a
Christmas tree, and an Easter

00:36:37.270 --> 00:36:38.514
egg hunt, and all that.

00:36:38.514 --> 00:36:39.930
My mother didn't
have any of that.

00:36:39.930 --> 00:36:41.980
So we had absolutely nothing.

00:36:41.980 --> 00:36:45.530
And unlike everyone else
who was from somewhere,

00:36:45.530 --> 00:36:47.540
my mother didn't know
where we were from.

00:36:47.540 --> 00:36:50.040
And I, at one point, talked to
my grandmother-- her mother--

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:51.370
and said, where are we from?

00:36:51.370 --> 00:36:53.070
My grandmother said, who knew?

00:36:53.070 --> 00:36:55.260
And I was like,
surely you must know

00:36:55.260 --> 00:36:56.550
where the family came from.

00:36:56.550 --> 00:36:57.050
Who knew?

00:36:57.050 --> 00:36:58.530
They kept changing the borders.

00:36:58.530 --> 00:37:01.360
So it was this sense
of we're from nowhere.

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:02.990
We don't believe in anything.

00:37:02.990 --> 00:37:05.260
And I had a very
innate spiritual sense.

00:37:05.260 --> 00:37:07.790
I went through a lot of
life or death experiences

00:37:07.790 --> 00:37:10.840
and really did feel at times
that I was being shepherded

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:14.430
by some otherworldly force,
but I had no vocabulary for it.

00:37:14.430 --> 00:37:16.130
So when I was nine,
my mother and I

00:37:16.130 --> 00:37:17.910
were living on the
side of this mountain,

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:20.960
and we passed a
cabin down the trail.

00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:23.260
And this guy who was-- I
don't know exactly what

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:25.550
he did-- but he lived in
Seattle, his vacation home,

00:37:25.550 --> 00:37:27.175
When he wanted to
get away from it all,

00:37:27.175 --> 00:37:29.837
he came and lived by our
main house where we lived.

00:37:29.837 --> 00:37:31.920
And my mother started
talking to him and, he said,

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:32.870
where are you from?

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:36.020
And my mother said, oh,
we're from San Francisco.

00:37:36.020 --> 00:37:39.200
And he goes, ain't no
landsman from the Bay Area,

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:40.527
no Jews from San Francisco.

00:37:40.527 --> 00:37:43.110
And my mother laughs, and said,
how'd you know we were Jewish.

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:43.830
And he said, look at your kid.

00:37:43.830 --> 00:37:45.150
He's got a rabbi's nose.

00:37:45.150 --> 00:37:47.840
And they started
talking and laughing.

00:37:47.840 --> 00:37:50.620
And finally he ended
his little soliloquy,

00:37:50.620 --> 00:37:53.110
and he said, so I must have
been the only Italian kid

00:37:53.110 --> 00:37:55.380
in Brooklyn with not one,
but two bar mitzvahs.

00:37:55.380 --> 00:37:58.064
And my mother thought this
was hilarious, and we left.

00:37:58.064 --> 00:38:00.480
And it was this strange moment
for me, where all of sudden

00:38:00.480 --> 00:38:01.600
there was some history.

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:05.440
This guy new things about
us, and strange places,

00:38:05.440 --> 00:38:09.110
and things beyond east
of the Mississippi.

00:38:09.110 --> 00:38:11.210
So when we got out into
the darkening mist,

00:38:11.210 --> 00:38:13.420
I asked my mother,
what are we again?

00:38:13.420 --> 00:38:16.410
That guy knew about us,
and my nose, and something.

00:38:16.410 --> 00:38:18.040
Aw yeah, we're Jews.

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:19.480
What does that mean?

00:38:19.480 --> 00:38:23.540
Well like Freud,
Einstein, Marks, Jews.

00:38:23.540 --> 00:38:25.400
So I thought about that.

00:38:25.400 --> 00:38:27.830
I was like, we're
related to them?

00:38:27.830 --> 00:38:30.010
Sort of.

00:38:30.010 --> 00:38:31.610
Then she gave me a
good Jewish answer.

00:38:31.610 --> 00:38:34.840
She said, we should go to
the library and look it up.

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:38.090
So when I finally got into
town and I went to the library,

00:38:38.090 --> 00:38:42.050
I really went in with no sense
of what I was looking for

00:38:42.050 --> 00:38:44.950
and came away with this
Encyclopedia Britannica

00:38:44.950 --> 00:38:49.080
introduction, which was so we're
descended from this ancient

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:53.400
tribe that wrote the Bible and
introduced the world to God

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:56.860
and is supposed to shine like
a beacon of righteousness.

00:38:56.860 --> 00:38:58.660
But the thing that
really touched me

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:01.420
about the Jewish story
that I read in this library

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:05.850
was that it mimicked my own
life, this nomadic wandering

00:39:05.850 --> 00:39:09.010
from place to place,
perpetually demeaned,

00:39:09.010 --> 00:39:12.250
and discriminated against
by various people,

00:39:12.250 --> 00:39:14.860
yet still thriving and
living by your wits.

00:39:14.860 --> 00:39:16.400
And that really
resonated with me.

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:19.080
So I think that was
my introduction.

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:20.916
And then as part of
that, I went and talked

00:39:20.916 --> 00:39:22.540
to my mother, who
then told me that she

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:24.330
had given up a
child for adoption.

00:39:24.330 --> 00:39:25.840
When she was a
teenager, she briefly

00:39:25.840 --> 00:39:28.730
dated a Colombian
Marxist revolutionary

00:39:28.730 --> 00:39:30.400
and had given up this
baby for adoption,

00:39:30.400 --> 00:39:32.930
and somewhere in New Jersey
I had a half brother.

00:39:32.930 --> 00:39:35.870
And somehow in my mind that
was that he was probably living

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:38.181
a Jewish life, because it
was New Jersey after all.

00:39:38.181 --> 00:39:39.930
And everyone in New
Jersey must be Jewish.

00:39:39.930 --> 00:39:41.870
And so I had this sense
that somewhere out there

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:44.161
were my people-- I didn't
know who or where they were--

00:39:44.161 --> 00:39:46.187
and someday he would
clasp me by the arm,

00:39:46.187 --> 00:39:48.270
and pull me up out of this
smashing and screaming,

00:39:48.270 --> 00:39:49.770
and take me home.

00:39:49.770 --> 00:39:51.960
So that became part
of my own mythology.

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:56.570
And then spiritually, a
couple years later, my mother

00:39:56.570 --> 00:40:00.350
had dated a Rastafarian
Mennonite-- which

00:40:00.350 --> 00:40:03.360
to give the picture--
no mustache,

00:40:03.360 --> 00:40:05.860
but chin beard and dreadlocks.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:10.020
And he made this mixtape
of reggae music for me.

00:40:10.020 --> 00:40:12.880
And so, my mother was obsessed
with Coltrane, and Miles Davis,

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:15.600
and this amazing jazz, which
was very traumatic for me

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:17.386
to listen to.

00:40:17.386 --> 00:40:18.760
But reggae really
appealed to me.

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:21.380
It had this melodic
spiritual sound to it.

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:23.235
And we're around
the campfire, and I

00:40:23.235 --> 00:40:25.840
was singing this Bob
Marley song, "the stone

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:29.140
that the builder refuse shall
be the head cornerstone".

00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:31.110
And I didn't know what
a head cornerstone was,

00:40:31.110 --> 00:40:33.750
but I knew that I had been the
stone that the builder refused,

00:40:33.750 --> 00:40:34.910
and that spoke to me.

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:37.160
And so I'm singing that
song, and my mother says,

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:38.810
oh, that's from Psalms.

00:40:38.810 --> 00:40:41.170
And I was like, this isn't
some weird bible thing.

00:40:41.170 --> 00:40:43.820
This is Bob Marley,
roots, truth.

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:45.640
And my Mom, no, no.

00:40:45.640 --> 00:40:49.350
She had this book, which
I called the Tonach, which

00:40:49.350 --> 00:40:51.120
was the Tondach--
the Hebrew Bible.

00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:53.290
So she gave me this book,
and I'm looking through.

00:40:53.290 --> 00:40:54.540
And I find the book
of Psalms and end up

00:40:54.540 --> 00:40:56.686
reading the whole thing
to just disprove her,

00:40:56.686 --> 00:40:58.060
because at that
point in my life,

00:40:58.060 --> 00:40:59.851
I'd rejected everything
that she was about.

00:40:59.851 --> 00:41:02.830
I thought, yes, you can hug
a child with nuclear arms.

00:41:02.830 --> 00:41:05.260
Like everything that she
believed in was wrong.

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:07.510
So I started working my way
through the book of Psalms

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:08.280
to disprove her.

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:09.620
I found out that she was right.

00:41:09.620 --> 00:41:10.880
That was a line from Psalms.

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:13.510
But I also read
Psalms is the poetry

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:17.640
of King David, a young man
in the wilderness crying out

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:18.650
for help.

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:21.390
And as I read that
book, I was like, this

00:41:21.390 --> 00:41:22.657
is like my experience.

00:41:22.657 --> 00:41:23.990
I'm really resonating with this.

00:41:23.990 --> 00:41:27.520
So that really became a
spiritual path for me, as well.

00:41:27.520 --> 00:41:30.077
And it provided the vocabulary
for the things that I

00:41:30.077 --> 00:41:31.660
was feeling, and a
sense of belonging,

00:41:31.660 --> 00:41:33.280
and a sense of identity.

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:35.090
And at a certain
point, my mother said,

00:41:35.090 --> 00:41:36.910
you're basically going
to be subscribing

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:39.055
to a rule based
patriarchal religion.

00:41:39.055 --> 00:41:40.090
And I thought about it.

00:41:40.090 --> 00:41:42.650
I was like, well, I had
no rules and no father,

00:41:42.650 --> 00:41:45.110
so that sounds about right.

00:41:45.110 --> 00:41:49.210
So that was that part
of my path began there.

00:41:49.210 --> 00:41:51.870
AUDIENCE: I have read the first
two chapters of your book.

00:41:51.870 --> 00:41:53.340
You're an amazing writer.

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:53.940
JOSHUA SAFRAN: Thank you.

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:54.440
Thank you.

00:41:54.440 --> 00:41:57.150
AUDIENCE: So do you have other
plan to write more books?

00:41:57.150 --> 00:41:59.040
JOSHUA SAFRAN: Yeah, I do.

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:02.570
I am working on a book proposal
for the sequel right now.

00:42:02.570 --> 00:42:04.790
So you'll see when you get
to the end of the book,

00:42:04.790 --> 00:42:08.730
it ends at 12 with us
running into this commune

00:42:08.730 --> 00:42:11.010
by the Canadian border
in a school bus.

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:15.840
And so it connects that kid
to being arrested a few times

00:42:15.840 --> 00:42:17.910
and being unsure
whether I was going

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:20.650
to make it out to making it out.

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:21.580
And thank you.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:23.750
I appreciate that.

00:42:23.750 --> 00:42:26.900
AUDIENCE: You talk a little bit
about why you became a lawyer,

00:42:26.900 --> 00:42:30.440
and it seems very disconnected
with what you ended up

00:42:30.440 --> 00:42:34.100
doing as your primary source
of income as a lawyer.

00:42:34.100 --> 00:42:38.410
I am also a corporate lawyer, so
take that with a grain of salt.

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:41.820
But how did you become
a corporate lawyer?

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:46.100
And were you ever able to
find more fulfillment in that

00:42:46.100 --> 00:42:50.470
than the Fortune 500
battle of 20 million?

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:54.922
JOSHUA SAFRAN: Yeah, so
I had twin aspirations

00:42:54.922 --> 00:42:55.880
in going to law school.

00:42:55.880 --> 00:42:57.510
Part of it was I
still to this day

00:42:57.510 --> 00:42:59.862
am actually offended
by lawyer jokes,

00:42:59.862 --> 00:43:02.070
because I still at least
have a perception in my mind

00:43:02.070 --> 00:43:04.620
most lawyers are these guardians
of justice doing great work.

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:07.090
How can you make that joke?

00:43:07.090 --> 00:43:09.620
And I'm sad that that's
probably not true.

00:43:09.620 --> 00:43:12.484
So I did have this sense,
both in my own personal life

00:43:12.484 --> 00:43:14.150
as far as criminal
defense attorneys who

00:43:14.150 --> 00:43:17.250
played an important role in my
life to keeping me out of jail,

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:18.280
for example.

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:19.810
I had a great
respect for lawyers,

00:43:19.810 --> 00:43:23.240
and I really saw them as
these uniquely capable people,

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:26.040
because they had the
monopoly of knowledge

00:43:26.040 --> 00:43:28.940
on how to navigate
the system, and yet

00:43:28.940 --> 00:43:31.130
were down dealing with
people like us who

00:43:31.130 --> 00:43:32.440
are outside of that system.

00:43:32.440 --> 00:43:34.370
So they were these
warriors, really.

00:43:34.370 --> 00:43:35.740
So that was on the one side.

00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:37.640
And the other side
is when you grow up

00:43:37.640 --> 00:43:39.750
with no running water,
electricity, and everything

00:43:39.750 --> 00:43:43.646
else, or sugar, or television,
that's all you want.

00:43:43.646 --> 00:43:45.520
You can guarantee that
your child will rebel.

00:43:45.520 --> 00:43:47.980
So for me, as I
was looking around,

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:50.960
I was like, OK, who
are successful people?

00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:53.850
And I had this lawyer thing,
and oh, yeah, lawyers do well.

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:55.640
Lawyers can-- that's a big deal.

00:43:55.640 --> 00:43:57.310
That's a respectable thing.

00:43:57.310 --> 00:43:58.394
So that was my motivation.

00:43:58.394 --> 00:43:59.810
And then when I
got to law school,

00:43:59.810 --> 00:44:02.500
I had this amazing awful moment,
which you may have experienced.

00:44:02.500 --> 00:44:03.875
Or you may have
experienced where

00:44:03.875 --> 00:44:06.710
you're like, I'm going to do
justice, and you're like, wow,

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:10.270
you have to live in a
trailer and eat canned beans

00:44:10.270 --> 00:44:12.840
to do the nonprofit work.

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:16.540
But these people will
pay you over six figures

00:44:16.540 --> 00:44:18.100
to just do whatever.

00:44:18.100 --> 00:44:19.620
That's awesome.

00:44:19.620 --> 00:44:23.440
And for me I was truly excited
about that opportunity.

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:26.070
And to be totally
clear, I loved it.

00:44:26.070 --> 00:44:29.300
I mean, I still to this day take
10 minute showers, and I mean,

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:30.717
I just love having everything.

00:44:30.717 --> 00:44:33.050
I gained a ton of weight,
because I could eat doughnuts,

00:44:33.050 --> 00:44:35.230
and it was great.

00:44:35.230 --> 00:44:38.860
See, I blame everything
on my childhood.

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:41.270
But no, so I mean, I was
enjoying all of that.

00:44:41.270 --> 00:44:43.680
And I loved all that that
got me, but at the same time

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:47.050
I think the hours expectations
in these big corporate firms

00:44:47.050 --> 00:44:49.390
are such that they don't
want you to do anything

00:44:49.390 --> 00:44:50.700
but be a corporate lawyer.

00:44:50.700 --> 00:44:52.200
And so I think that
was really the--

00:44:52.200 --> 00:44:53.750
I still have great
respect for people

00:44:53.750 --> 00:44:57.060
who can integrate pro bono work
into their corporate practice.

00:44:57.060 --> 00:44:58.250
I mean, it's righteous.

00:44:58.250 --> 00:45:01.209
For me, I ended up--
sadly when people

00:45:01.209 --> 00:45:03.500
say this movie must have been
so great for your career.

00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:06.230
I'm like, it destroyed
my partnership prospects,

00:45:06.230 --> 00:45:07.580
and I got fired.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:09.240
But that's what happened.

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:10.906
I was at the firm, I
was up for partner,

00:45:10.906 --> 00:45:13.270
and they said, look dude,
you do way too much pro bono.

00:45:13.270 --> 00:45:15.664
You need to be
kicking up your hours.

00:45:15.664 --> 00:45:17.580
And it's great you're
representing this woman,

00:45:17.580 --> 00:45:18.371
but enough already.

00:45:18.371 --> 00:45:20.370
It's been eight years.

00:45:20.370 --> 00:45:24.131
So at that point, I left and
still was working on her case

00:45:24.131 --> 00:45:24.630
actually.

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:27.845
And then I was lucky enough that
my current day job-- the Port

00:45:27.845 --> 00:45:29.970
of Oakland called, and I
had been representing them

00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:30.880
as outside counsel.

00:45:30.880 --> 00:45:32.270
And they said, come in-house.

00:45:32.270 --> 00:45:33.575
And I was, well, I'll
need all these days off

00:45:33.575 --> 00:45:34.533
for my parole hearings.

00:45:34.533 --> 00:45:36.660
And they're like, what
are you talking about?

00:45:36.660 --> 00:45:38.390
You're like the
aviation, land use,

00:45:38.390 --> 00:45:41.050
all of these areas of
expertise I had cultivated.

00:45:41.050 --> 00:45:43.320
And I explained it
to the person who

00:45:43.320 --> 00:45:46.480
was I thought about
not to give me a job.

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:50.617
And much credit to my boss who
then said, that sounds really

00:45:50.617 --> 00:45:52.450
righteous, this case
that you're working on.

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:53.420
I'll make a deal with you.

00:45:53.420 --> 00:45:55.461
And I was like, OK, what's
this deal going to be?

00:45:55.461 --> 00:45:58.120
He's like, when you get her
out, you bring her up here,

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:00.411
and we'll have a lunch for her.

00:46:00.411 --> 00:46:01.750
And I was like, all right.

00:46:01.750 --> 00:46:03.690
Good deal.

00:46:03.690 --> 00:46:07.534
I'm a government lawyer,
so it has worked out.

00:46:07.534 --> 00:46:08.950
Well the one other
thing that I'll

00:46:08.950 --> 00:46:12.960
say just because I know that
maybe my mother-- this very

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:17.110
interesting character but also
a very interesting person-- we

00:46:17.110 --> 00:46:18.730
grew up together.

00:46:18.730 --> 00:46:20.920
When I went to college,
my mother went to college.

00:46:20.920 --> 00:46:24.610
When I got a job, she got a job.

00:46:24.610 --> 00:46:26.930
I had years of
resentment and anger

00:46:26.930 --> 00:46:29.080
to her for what I
began to perceive

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:32.430
as the unnecessary deprivation
that we had to go through.

00:46:32.430 --> 00:46:35.730
In a way, I could almost forgive
her for the domestic violence

00:46:35.730 --> 00:46:37.990
years, because I understood
the dynamic of how

00:46:37.990 --> 00:46:39.950
we'd gotten in there
and how we got out.

00:46:39.950 --> 00:46:42.574
But all the other
stuff, the deprivation.

00:46:42.574 --> 00:46:43.990
And then I got to
college, and I'm

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:47.100
meeting all these kids who grew
up in cul-de-sacs and suburbs,

00:46:47.100 --> 00:46:49.720
eating sugar, watching
television, having hot showers,

00:46:49.720 --> 00:46:52.120
all the rest of it,
and I get to college,

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:53.625
and they're like this sucks.

00:46:53.625 --> 00:46:54.890
I don't want to be here.

00:46:54.890 --> 00:46:57.680
This is lame, and my
mother never loved me,

00:46:57.680 --> 00:46:59.344
and my father likes
my brother more.

00:46:59.344 --> 00:47:01.760
And they never had any domestic
violence or anything else,

00:47:01.760 --> 00:47:03.370
but they were
totally bummed out.

00:47:03.370 --> 00:47:05.230
And I'm in college
thinking, this

00:47:05.230 --> 00:47:07.500
is the greatest
experience of my life.

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:09.161
I can just go to
the dining hall,

00:47:09.161 --> 00:47:10.910
and there's just as
much food as you want.

00:47:10.910 --> 00:47:12.300
It's like Google.

00:47:12.300 --> 00:47:13.780
You can take these showers.

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:14.997
You watch television.

00:47:14.997 --> 00:47:15.830
You can do anything.

00:47:15.830 --> 00:47:17.204
I was just like,
this is amazing.

00:47:17.204 --> 00:47:17.896
I was loving it.

00:47:17.896 --> 00:47:19.270
And so part of me
was like, well,

00:47:19.270 --> 00:47:22.200
there's different ways
of judging a parent,

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:24.330
but I always felt like
my mother loved me.

00:47:24.330 --> 00:47:25.430
I always felt like
she was like, you

00:47:25.430 --> 00:47:26.620
can do anything you want to do.

00:47:26.620 --> 00:47:28.090
You can be anyone
you want to be.

00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:30.970
She may not have supervised me.

00:47:30.970 --> 00:47:32.350
But she loved me.

00:47:32.350 --> 00:47:35.070
And so I began to
recalibrate my own feelings

00:47:35.070 --> 00:47:36.630
toward my mother at that point.

00:47:36.630 --> 00:47:41.350
And she, around that
time, said, I turned on,

00:47:41.350 --> 00:47:44.950
tuned in, dropped out, but
I'm finally crawling back.

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:46.510
And that was her
sense, that she was

00:47:46.510 --> 00:47:48.970
going to rejoin-- she was
going to wave the white flag.

00:47:48.970 --> 00:47:51.370
The revolution was
not coming tomorrow,

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:53.730
and she was going to
rejoin American society.

00:47:53.730 --> 00:47:56.230
Now that said, when the whole
Occupy Movement was happening,

00:47:56.230 --> 00:47:58.480
my mother was like,
oh, this could be it.

00:47:58.480 --> 00:48:00.770
Get ready.

00:48:00.770 --> 00:48:04.500
So she's still looking
forward to the revolution,

00:48:04.500 --> 00:48:06.580
but she also has a mortgage.

00:48:06.580 --> 00:48:10.030
So it's been an
interesting relationship.

00:48:10.030 --> 00:48:12.320
And my wife and I, we
actually trust her.

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:14.350
She comes and babysits.

00:48:14.350 --> 00:48:16.154
We have three daughters.

00:48:16.154 --> 00:48:17.320
But it's like, we come back.

00:48:17.320 --> 00:48:18.952
It's 10:00 at night.

00:48:18.952 --> 00:48:20.410
All the lights in
the house are on.

00:48:20.410 --> 00:48:21.782
None of the girls are in bed.

00:48:21.782 --> 00:48:22.740
One of them is missing.

00:48:22.740 --> 00:48:24.455
One's watching something
on the computer.

00:48:24.455 --> 00:48:25.460
Who knows what?

00:48:25.460 --> 00:48:27.830
And she's playing the
maracas with the youngest.

00:48:27.830 --> 00:48:33.370
So she's still pretty spirited,
but has really come a long way.

00:48:33.370 --> 00:48:36.840
And we still have a
very close relationship.

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:39.770
Yeah, so I mean, I think one
of the things that surprised me

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:43.250
when I began part
of my strange arc.

00:48:43.250 --> 00:48:46.100
We all have our weird arcs,
but my weird arc was the thing

00:48:46.100 --> 00:48:47.680
that you're most
ashamed of is going

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:49.470
to be your defining
characteristic, which

00:48:49.470 --> 00:48:51.847
is-- if you think about what
that is in your life, that's

00:48:51.847 --> 00:48:53.430
a really weird thing
to have happened.

00:48:53.430 --> 00:48:54.670
So it happened to me.

00:48:54.670 --> 00:48:56.670
I didn't want to ever
talk about this issue that

00:48:56.670 --> 00:48:57.540
had happened to me.

00:48:57.540 --> 00:48:59.320
And there was just
this thirst to have

00:48:59.320 --> 00:49:02.590
me come speak
about these issues.

00:49:02.590 --> 00:49:06.130
And a big part of that has
been the fact that I'm a man,

00:49:06.130 --> 00:49:08.170
and I didn't realize
this until I got into it.

00:49:08.170 --> 00:49:11.170
But the perception out there
is that domestic violence

00:49:11.170 --> 00:49:12.150
is a women's issue.

00:49:12.150 --> 00:49:14.020
It's women get in
these relationships,

00:49:14.020 --> 00:49:18.100
and women get battered, and
women do leave or don't leave,

00:49:18.100 --> 00:49:18.830
and whatever.

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:21.590
But there's this whole missing
equation of for every victim,

00:49:21.590 --> 00:49:23.270
there's a perpetrator.

00:49:23.270 --> 00:49:26.750
And this identity of, wait a
second, why isn't it a man's

00:49:26.750 --> 00:49:27.250
issue?

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:29.249
So a lot of the work that
I've been trying to do

00:49:29.249 --> 00:49:32.000
is to talk about--
especially with young guys--

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:33.620
what it means to
be a man, and what

00:49:33.620 --> 00:49:36.930
it means to stand up for someone
who's weaker than you are,

00:49:36.930 --> 00:49:39.040
and not to bully them.

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:42.770
And I think that one of the
strange realizations that I've

00:49:42.770 --> 00:49:45.090
had-- that the science
shows, of course--

00:49:45.090 --> 00:49:46.720
is that the
perpetrators, the men who

00:49:46.720 --> 00:49:49.520
are in these abusive
relationships, the batterers

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:53.510
were themselves victims, or
at least children in homes

00:49:53.510 --> 00:49:54.645
where this was happening.

00:49:54.645 --> 00:49:56.020
So there's this
strange arc where

00:49:56.020 --> 00:49:59.064
these boys, like me, who you
can be very sympathetic to,

00:49:59.064 --> 00:50:00.730
and say, OK, well,
it's not their fault.

00:50:00.730 --> 00:50:01.396
They're a child.

00:50:01.396 --> 00:50:02.320
It's not their fault.

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:03.300
They're a child.

00:50:03.300 --> 00:50:04.200
Now it's their fault.

00:50:04.200 --> 00:50:08.390
They're now 17 and in an
abusive relationship themselves.

00:50:08.390 --> 00:50:10.865
And the way that the human
mind works with these boys who

00:50:10.865 --> 00:50:13.690
are seeing what
happens, part of what's

00:50:13.690 --> 00:50:16.350
going on in their head is
they're thinking, well,

00:50:16.350 --> 00:50:18.870
what's wrong in this
equation is not necessarily

00:50:18.870 --> 00:50:21.500
that he's beating
my mother or running

00:50:21.500 --> 00:50:22.570
the house like a tyrant.

00:50:22.570 --> 00:50:25.490
What's wrong is that
I'm not the alpha.

00:50:25.490 --> 00:50:27.490
I'm not the king, but
someday I will be.

00:50:27.490 --> 00:50:30.670
And then it will be OK,
because I'll be in control.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:33.110
And it's about breaking
that whole cycle,

00:50:33.110 --> 00:50:35.190
and it really is this
a generational notion.

00:50:35.190 --> 00:50:36.856
And the last thing I
will say about that

00:50:36.856 --> 00:50:41.045
is if you think the statistics
are that somewhere between one

00:50:41.045 --> 00:50:43.170
in four and one in three
women will experience this

00:50:43.170 --> 00:50:46.460
in their lifetimes, which means
roughly the same number of men

00:50:46.460 --> 00:50:47.820
will be involved.

00:50:47.820 --> 00:50:49.420
And if you think
about it hard enough,

00:50:49.420 --> 00:50:51.920
you can probably think either
an experience that you've had,

00:50:51.920 --> 00:50:54.900
obviously, but a neighbor,
a friend, a colleague who

00:50:54.900 --> 00:50:58.480
you suspect, oh, yeah, this may
be happening in their lives.

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:00.890
I think the greatest
mistake is to be like, well,

00:51:00.890 --> 00:51:01.890
that's a private matter.

00:51:01.890 --> 00:51:03.120
I'm not going to pry.

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:05.000
I think we all have a
sense of how far you

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:08.889
can pry before you're committing
a crime, some kind of stalking

00:51:08.889 --> 00:51:09.430
or something.

00:51:09.430 --> 00:51:10.340
I don't want you to do that.

00:51:10.340 --> 00:51:12.620
But at the same time, that you
really do need to speak up.

00:51:12.620 --> 00:51:14.870
You do need to get involved,
and you will be surprised

00:51:14.870 --> 00:51:18.132
that when you do, people, I
think, will react in such a way

00:51:18.132 --> 00:51:20.540
that you're really glad
and happy that you did.

00:51:20.540 --> 00:51:22.130
And when you
intervene, it does help

00:51:22.130 --> 00:51:24.511
to break that cycle of violence.

00:51:24.511 --> 00:51:25.010
Thank you.

00:51:25.010 --> 00:51:27.640
MALE SPEAKER: Thank
you very much, Joshua.

